Recap

After looking at the data in different ways we see that their are subtle changes based on each category and parameter in the Database. The main takeaways so far are as follows:

  1. The Outlet Categories are predictive of the amount of total sales, this is most likely due to size of the outlet and ability to move more customers through in a day.
  2. The Different Outlet Types sell product more or less in the same distribution with the heavy categories being Snacks and Fruits and Vegetables.
  3. With the increase of sale price there is no real fluctuation of units sold. The more expencive products still move the same amount of invintory as those that are less expencive.
  4. With the knowledge of units sold not be effected by an increase in sales price for the most part we confermed this by Looking at the increase in MRP we see an increase in revenue, again conferming that there is no real decrease in units sold.
  5. Looking at Item Visibility in the Outlet based on Item Type we see a slight decrease actuly in units sold based on an increase in visibility although very slight and most likely negligable. and given that the heavier items have a higher visibility due to their size thus impacting the number of units sold as some customers might be traveling by different methods of transportation.

Machine Learning for predicting sales on possible new products

With the Data Exploration for the most part behind us I will now start on developing and refining a ML algarithm that can best predict the sales of new items the company might be conciderting to develop or source from another vendor. The key attributes that will go into the Calculator are:

  1. Item Type: To give a reference on expected units sold.
  2. Item Weight: As this will help determine its impact on visibility in the store.
  3. Vendors MRP: Recomended sale price from the vendor
  4. Item Fat Content: more refined Item Type

This ML Model will be a test between KNN and Linear Regression of the previously stated characteristics of a product.
